{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9a78e48c-1d23-4497-b2d6-ec278131095a","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues I found:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Recursive wildcard glob (`**\\*.*`) — **High impact**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThe double-star glob forces MSBuild to walk the **entire directory tree** on every evaluation. This is the single most common cause of slow evaluation, especially in repos with `node_modules`, large `obj`/`bin` leftovers, or many files. Prefer explicit file extensions (e.g. `**\\*.txt`) or a narrower directory scope.\n\n### 2. File I/O via property function — **Medium impact**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n`ReadAllText` executes **during evaluation**, not during build. Property functions that perform disk I/O block the evaluator and bypass MSBuild's caching. Move this to a target (e.g. `ReadLinesFromFile` task) so it only runs at build time.\n\n### 3. Three-level deep import chain — **Low-medium impact**\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach `<Import>` adds an XML parse + evaluation pass. Three levels is manageable, but it's a pattern that compounds: every extra level multiplies the evaluation work. Flatten when imports only set one property each.\n\n---\n\n**Recommended priority:** Fix #1 (wildcard glob) first — it typically dominates evaluation time. Then eliminate #2 (file read). The import chain (#3) is a minor contributor here but worth noting as a scaling concern.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4d8d41e3-f474-4299-b1cf-acd40ef87f81","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a complete picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.","outputTokens":454},"id":"29b20327-f46b-46b3-b7db-6195d4326fb8","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:07:43.413Z","parentId":"94021818-2dea-400c-b4f5-fc04772497f4"}
